Denote by (\alpha, \beta, \gamma) a normal vector of P. Then, the length of this vector must be 1 i.e. \[ \alpha^2 + \beta^2 + \gamma^2 = 1.\]Furthermore, \[\begin{pmatrix} \frac{2}{3} \\ -\frac{1}{3} \\ -\frac{2}{3} \end{pmatrix}\] is a direction vector of P. Applying the dot product of these vectors must lead to 0 i.e. \[\frac{2}{3}\alpha - \frac{1}{3}\beta - \frac{2}{3}\gamma = 0.\]Similarly, \[\begin{pmatrix} \frac{2}{15} \\ \frac{14}{15} \\ -\frac{1}{3} \end{pmatrix}\] is another direction vector of P. Applying the dot product of these vectors must lead to 0 i.e. \[\frac{2}{15}\alpha + \frac{14}{15}\beta - \frac{1}{3}\gamma = 0.\]We get a equation system consisting of these two equations as follows:\begin{align*}
&\left\{\begin{aligned}
& \beta + \gamma = 0, \\
& \alpha - \beta - \gamma = 0. 
\end{aligned} \right.  
\end{align*}Solving this equation system gives \begin{align*} \alpha &= \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}, \\ \beta &= -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}, \\ \gamma &= \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}, \end{align*}However, it contradicts the condition that $\alpha > 0$. Multiplying both sides by $\sqrt{2}$ and multiplying them to $-1$ gives $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}}$.</think> <answer> $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}}$ </answer>

